content.description: The left-most line on grey overhanging wall. Climbs the overhanging face and briefly utilizes the arete. Bouldery crux on the arete after bolt 3, followed by a no-hands rest, and a pumpy second half on good crimps and finger jugs.
content.protection: 8 bolts plus chains on the anchor
content.location: The obvious arete just to the left of the spot where the trail meets the wall.

content.description:
Fun, sustained face climbing once you get past the first two ledges.

Start on a small pile of blocks with a cool left hand pocket and pull onto the first ledge. Move right and up to another ledge above. Launch onto the face pulling on good, crisp edges and the occasional pocket on up to the chains just down and left of the big U-shaped tree at the top of the cliff.
content.location: The right-most of the three 5.11 routes on the wall just to the left at the end of the old oil road.

content.description: Long adventure route starting off a cheater stack with a boulder problem just over the trail. A crazy juggy roof finish awaits above.
content.location: Between the 5.11 wall and Synthetic Intermediate (mixed pro route) and Plate for the Party, just above the trail

content.description: Another interesting moderate on the plated face right of Poop Chute.
content.location: From the top of the old oil road approach, turn left going up a short hill and walk back to the left along the base of the wall passing the projects with ropes hanging and a big cow hip bone. Turn the corner of the wall and the two 5.10 routes will be on your right.

content.description: Starts left of a big chossy hole in the wall and climbs to a ledge at the first bolt, then through a series of technical mini ledges with an occasional side pull.
content.location: The rightmost of three sport lines  about 150 feet left of Valsalva Maneuver

content.description: Climb up the slab through some thin moves between the first three bolts. Kicks back for the last two bolts and anchors.
content.location: Walk about 50 yards left from the end of the steep section of wall where Charlie Horse(Swim Test) is located. Squeeze through a narrow section of trail between a huge boulder on left and the cliff on the right. The trail widens at the start of the climb.

content.description: Smear through dirt and moss to a cleaner headwall. Utilize the side of the crack and tech your way up to the top.
content.location: Follows the brown water runnel just left of the crack, the bottom is probably covered in a blanket of moss.

content.description:
With sustained technical pulling on flat edges on a slightly overhanging wall, this line has a distinctly different feel for the RRG.

Clamber up onto the initial shelf aiming for good holds up an angling flake. Take the flake up and left leading to great flat edge and edge up the face. Hang on until the final perfectly positioned small diving board to clip the anchors.
content.location: The middle of the three 5.11 routes on the wall just to the left at the end of the old oil road.

content.description: Follow the arete up past some steep moves. Jugs are right where you need them.
content.location: The arete to the right of the big steep area where Swim Test is.

content.description: Far left black streak route. High-quality movement, but bring a brush.
content.location: From the top of the old oil road approach, turn left going up a short hill and walk back to the left along the base of the wall passing the projects with ropes hanging and a big cow hip bone. Turn the corner of the wall and the two 5.10 routes will be on your right.

content.description: Route slowly kicks back after the hueco until a defined crux at the roof.
content.location: Middle of the small section of wall between with an OW/chimney corner to the left, and Realty Check to the right.

content.description: Obvious dihedral system on the right end of the ledge system.
content.location: [Needs location]

content.description: Starts of a cheater stone uphill of Synthetic, roof start to cool plates.
content.location: From the top of the old oil road approach, go straight (be careful not to muddy your feet in the small swamp) under the huge cave and contour around the wall to the right. Pass under the undercut roof start of Swan Dive and up a short hill to the base of this route.

content.description: Easy climbing for the first thirty feet in the dihedral. Solid gear for the upper section in horizontal cracks, with much harder moves ten feet from the anchors.
content.location: 50 yards from the end of the steep wall. From Stormy Weather walk up the trail left and start in a heavily featured obtuse dihedral.

content.description: Iron ledges led to a slight bulge in the middle, then cruise to the end.
content.location: Left and uphill and around the corner from Stormy Weather. The sport route between two cracks on the right face.

content.description: Starts on the right side of a slabby wall. Head to a ledge and small roof past the first bolt, then make some technical moves past a bulge and up into slab territory near the top.
content.location: Walk about 100 feet past the three 5.11 sport climbs at the top of the approach trail and around the corner to a slab wall.

content.description: Climb past a bulge to thin ledges and a tricky finish.
content.location: Left of the mossy black runnel

content.description: Climb the iron ledges to just before the third bolt, then tackle hard moves possibly including some chimney action in the wide crack.
content.location: Far left sport route at the far left of RDE. Start just left of a wide crack. This area is about 200 yards from the end of the approach trail.

content.description: Boulder start to a more vertical second half.
content.location: Start on the boulder left of the mossy black runnel

content.description: Start ten feet right of the arete and climb on small ledges past a small bulge near halfway to a slab finish
content.location: 150 feet left of Valsalva Maneuver, the leftmost of three bolted face climbs.

content.description: Mostly slabby but with a variety of underclings and side pull moves to keep the grade down. Ledge between 1st and 2nd bolts has some sandy spots but the working holds are good.
content.location: 100 feet left of the top of the approach trail. The second route from the right once you go around the corner. A couple of small steps lead to the base of this climb.

content.description: Start up through some small fingertip jugs to small ledges with some technical moves.
content.location: The middle of three sport routes about 150 feet left of Valsalva Maneuver.

content.description: Make your way up a short flake to thin technical ledges above.
content.location: Starts just left of Hunkered Down on a dirty slab. Brush your feet and go!

content.description: Starts a few few feet right of the obvious Omega dihedral from a small pedestal. Interesting plates and crimps lead up a beautiful licheny pillar of rock.
content.location: From the top of the old oil road approach, go straight (be careful not to muddy your feet in the small swamp) under the huge cave and contour around the wall to the right. Pass under the undercut roof start of Swan Dive and up a short hill to a ledge. This route is just to the right of the obvious dihedral.

content.description: Heavily featured first half with some intense off width and chimney moves on second half.
content.protection: Normal rack with plenty of long runners if you put your cams in deep or bring a few big pieces. Share the anchors with the sport route to the left.
content.location: The wide crack/dihedral at the far left end of RDE Far  left.

content.description: Just before the obvious dihedral up on the nice ledge system. Delicate crux to an unexpected pump. Bring a brush to love this one into shape.
content.location: From the top of the old oil road approach, go straight (be careful not to muddy your feet in the small swamp) under the huge cave and contour around the wall to the right. Pass under the undercut roof start of Swan Dive and up a short hill to a ledge and the base of this route.
